      <hedline>
        <hl1>D-Day, Over Here</hl1>
      </hedline>
      <abstract>
        <p>Alfred Gescheidt letter recalls repairing landing craft at naval base in Virginia during World War II (S)</p>
      </abstract>
    </body.head>
    <body.content>
      <block class="lead_paragraph">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''How D-Day Was Won'' (editorial, June 7):</p>
        <p>I was a yeoman in the Navy during World War II, and when people would ask me what I did, I'd say:  ''Nothing. I was stuck on a repair base.''</p>
      </block>
      <block class="full_text">
        <p>To the Editor:</p>
        <p>Re ''How D-Day Was Won'' (editorial, June 7):</p>
        <p>I was a yeoman in the Navy during World War II, and when people would ask me what I did, I'd say:  ''Nothing. I was stuck on a repair base.''</p>
        <p>It was there at the United States Naval Amphibious Base in Little Creek, Va., that we repaired landing craft (the LCVP's you mention) and their diesel engines, and I can still hear the hum of these engines tested day and night, in and out of the water.</p>
        <p>It's good to be reminded that without these ''Higgins'' boats, D-Day on Normandy might have been even more difficult. You have also given me a sense of pride that working there was important.</p>
        <p>ALFRED GESCHEIDT  New York, June 7, 2000</p>
      </block>
